Introduction¶

When it comes to the job market surronding data scientists, many people do not know where to start because of all of the daunting job titles and other things that come with applying. The purpose of this project is to take a dataset about the pay of data scientists and really breakdown what is going on and how a new data scientist can break into the field and put themselves out there. Knowing what you should be paid and what others are being paid is a very string tool as a interviewee and can allow you to get an upperhand when in an interview

6-10 Questions¶

  1. what country has the best pay for data scientists?

  2. What are the most common job titles among data scientists?

  3. How does employment type (e.g., full-time, part-time, contract) vary among data scientists?

  4. What is the distribution of experience levels (e.g., entry-level, mid-level, senior) among data scientists?

  5. Is there a correlation between expertise level (e.g., beginner, intermediate, expert) and salary for data scientists?
  1. Does the size of the company (e.g., small, medium, large) impact the salary of data scientists?
  1. What are some trends in salaries over the years?

In [19]:
top_job_titles = df['Job Title'].value_counts().head(10).index.tolist()
df_top_n = df[df['Job Title'].isin(top_job_titles)]
count_data = df_top_n.groupby(['Job Title', 'Experience Level']).size().unstack(fill_value=0)
count_data.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, figsize=(12, 6))
plt.title(f'Top {10} Job Titles by Experience Level')
plt.xlabel('Job Title')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.legend(title='Experience Level')
plt.show()

In this graph we can see the top 10 Job titles in our dataset (too many job titles to include all) of these top 10 job titles, it is easy to observe that a majority of them are controlled by senior data scientists showing to an entry level data scientist that maybe these are some titles to stay away from until they have some experience under thier belt.

average_salary = df.groupby('Year')['Salary in USD'].mean()
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(average_salary.index, average_salary.values, marker='o', linestyle='-')
plt.title('Average Salary Over the Years')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Average Salary (USD)')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

With this graph we can see that from 2020 to 2021 there was a slight decine but after we had a sharp increase in the salaries and after a tiny drop. This is somehting that we will continue to see as time goes on because Data science is an evergrowing field and will always be improving and being built on. so for the forseeable future data science is seeming to be a very stable job.

Takeaways¶

When examining our collected data and piecing together the bigger picture, several observations emerge. Let's start with experience levelit's common knowledge that as one gains more knowledge in their field, their pay increases accordingly. However, the amount of this pay increase is often not widely understood. through out analysis, we highlighted a significant finding: senior data scientists earn up to twice as much as entry-level counterparts. This insight is extremely helpful, providing clear information for entry-level job seekers about higher-paying roles and emphasizing the rewards of perseverance and dedication in career advancement. Additonally, it lets these seekers understand what they should be paid in years to come and allows them to have a sort of upperhand in job interviews by knowing what they are worth.

Moving on to the question of which job titles offer the best pay, we uncover valuable data by comparing this inquiry with the graph sorting job titles by experience level. This approach allows us to locate roles that not only offer competitive salaries but also welcome entry-level candidates. While some higher-paying positions may require more experience, the dataset still presents starting points for those on their journey in data science. For example, An ML engineer is #10 on our list for job titles witht the highest pay but is almost all made up of senior and executive data scientists meaning that it is probably something that an entry-level scientist should not be looking into.

considering the Location of a company, understanding which countries offer the highest pay is particularly relevant in today's landscape, where remote work is increasingly sought after. This information serves as a valuable resource for individuals exploring remote work opportunities and seeking locations with favorable pay. Although this isn't something most people think about when applying for jobs it is still something to consider.

it's important to acknowledge the limitations within the dataset. For instance, inaccuracies stemming from outliers, such as the high salary in Qatar, can skew results. We can see this in two seperate graphs where the leading role is $400K, a number that no other title was even close to, thus making it an outlier. While seasoned data scientists can readily identify and address such outliers, beginners may overlook them.

In summary, while the dataset offers straightforward insights and facilitates easy comparisons between variables, it's essential to keep an eye out for potential outliers and exercise caution in drawing conclusions. By leveraging the dataset's strengths and addressing its limitations, we can gain valuable insights to inform beginners need in order to break through in this field and get the pay that they deserve.
